{{Quote|Look, good against remotes is one thing. Good against the living? That's something else.|[[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]] to [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]]|<ref name="Episode 4">{{Film|IV}}</ref>}}
The '''Marksman-H combat remote''', also referred to as a '''seeker droid'''<ref name="Hero for Hire">''[[Star Wars Journal: Hero for Hire]]''</ref> and '''training remote''', was a [[Remote/Legends|remote]] used for military training. Manufactured by [[Industrial Automaton/Legends|Industrial Automaton]], it was equipped with non-lethal [[Blaster/Legends|blasters]] to prevent injuries to the target. 

The fast-moving and unpredictable remote was commonly used by marksmen to improve reaction time and aiming skills. In order to prevent damage, remotes were usually shot at with light-only blasts. Many smugglers and [[Bounty hunter/Legends|bounty hunters]] also used remotes to perfect their quick-draw skills. Most famously, [[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]] owned and practiced with a Marksman-H model training remote.

==Description==
The Marksman-H combat remote was a model of [[Remote/Legends|remote]] manufactured by [[Industrial Automaton/Legends|Industrial Automaton]].<ref name="EGWT" /> Costing 350 [[Galactic Credit Standard/Legends|credits]],<ref name="RPGCR" /> the remote was spherical, measuring thirty-two [[Centimeter/Legends|centimeters]] in diameter,<ref name="NEGWT" /> and was covered with [[laser emitter]]s, [[Sensor/Legends|sensors]], and [[Maneuvering jet/Legends|maneuvering thrusters]].<ref name="EGWT" /> The Marksman-H possessed a rudimentary [[Computer/Legends|computer]] brain, a short-range [[Sensor array/Legends|sensor array]], and low-grade [[Deflector shield/Legends|deflector shields]].<ref name="NEGWT" /> The unit was controlled through a [[handheld signaler]] that emitted high-pitched coded bursts, and could be controlled in an emergency by a verbal override code.<ref name="EGWT" />

A small [[Repulsorlift/Legends|repulsorlift]] generator was housed underneath the remote's casing which allowed the Marksman-H to move at a top speed of twenty-five [[Kilometer/Legends|kilometers]] an [[Standard hour/Legends|hour]]. The remote had a high degree of maneuverability, provided by the eight maneuvering thrusters, allowing the remote to make sharp turns and height adjustments, as well as fast acceleration and deceleration.<ref name="EGWT" /> The [[emitter nozzle]]s on the Marksman-H could be configured to emit a variety of substances, including stun blasts, compressed air, non-lethal [[Gas/Legends|gases]], light beams, or audio emanations.<ref name="NEGWT" /> 

The Marksman-H was used to instruct [[Sniper/Legends|snipers]] and help them hone their skills.<ref name="NEGWT" /> The sharpshooter's blaster was recalibrated to emit light only, and hits on the remote were registered by the unit's sensors. The remote's [[Computer/Legends|computer]] was pre-programmed with a number of combat drills that were set to conclude either after an allotted time had elapsed, or a number of hits on the unit were scored.<ref name="EGWT" />

The Marksman-H could run drills from novice levels where the remote moved slowly and the [[Stun blaster/Legends|stun blaster]] was disabled, to expert levels where the remote weaved around the trainee attempting to hit them with [[Stun/Legends|stun]] blasts.<ref name="EGWT" /> Training sessions could move through training levels, increasing the intensity and accuracy of the stun blasts.<ref name="NEGWT" /> In addition to be used in the training of blaster combat, Marksman-H remotes were also effective in the instruction of [[Lightsaber/Legends|lightsaber]], forcing the trainee to deflect numerous stun blasts while waiting for an opportunity to strike.<ref name="EGWT" /> 

The laser emitters were [[Stun blaster/Legends|stun blasters]] with variable intensity levels, ranging from a light discharge that caused the part of the body that was struck to tingle momentarily to a heavier discharge that could fully numb an [[Limb/Legends|arm]] or leg.<ref name="EGWT" /> In some cases, the blast could render a person unconscious. The blasters had an optimal range of four [[Meter/Legends|meters]] and a maximum range of thirty-five.<ref name="NEGWT" /> The firing rate of the blaster was determined by the difficulty level that the remote was operating under, and the unit was capable of firing at twice a [[Standard second|second]] at the highest level. The accuracy of the blasters were also variable, becoming extremely precise as the difficulty level got more advanced.<ref name="EGWT" />

==History==
[[File:Training_remote.jpg|thumb|left|[[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo's]] Marksman-H]]
During the time of the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]], [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] [[Youngling/Legends|younglings]] would practice [[Form I/Legends|Form I/Shii-Cho]] with these remotes. Indeed, the younglings were using them, under supervision of [[Yoda/Legends|Yoda]], when [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]] came to them for help in locating [[Kamino/Legends|Kamino]]. Some variants, however, were modified for actual combat in case the Jedi Temple was attacked, as was demonstrated during [[Operation: Knightfall/Legends|Operation: Knightfall]].<ref name="GBA/DS">[[Star Wars: Episode III Revenge of the Sith (video game)|''Star Wars'': Episode III ''Revenge of the Sith'' video game]]; Anakin scenario (GBA/DS version)</ref>

They were also used as shooting-range targets as part of the training of [[Clone trooper/Legends|clone]] [[Sniper/Legends|sharpshooters]] during the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]].<ref name="Star Wars: The Clone Wars: Sharpshooter">{{SWArchive|url=games/playnow/sharpshooter|text=Sharpshooter|int=Sharpshooter (game)}}</ref>

After the [[Declaration of a New Order|birth]] of the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]], several Marksman-H combat remotes were modified to carry out executions to enemies of the Empire. These execution droids would wander population centers and scan for enemies of the Empire based on the identities of known targets stored in their memory banks. Upon locating them, the targets would be executed on the spot.<ref name="Galaxy7">{{GalaxyCite|6|Predators of the Empire}}</ref>

The [[Smuggler/Legends|smuggler]] [[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]] kept a Marksman-H aboard the ''[[Millennium Falcon/Legends|Millennium Falcon]]'', using it for target practice.<ref name="EGWT" /> While on board the [[Starship/Legends|ship]] on route to [[Alderaan/Legends|Alderaan]], [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] began his [[Lightsaber/Legends|lightsaber]] training under [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]] using the remote. Skywalker could not predict what the remote would do, but Kenobi blocked his vision with a [[Helmet/Legends|helmet]] equipped with an opaque [[Blast shield/Legends|blast shield]] to encourage him to use [[The Force/Legends|the Force]] rather than his physical vision. After a little more practice, he managed to block the droid's weapons fire.<ref name="ANH">{{Film|IV}}</ref>

{{Droid-stub}}

==Behind the scenes==
The training remote Luke practices with in [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''A New Hope'']] was originally conceived as an automated execution droid used by the Empire.<ref name="Galaxy7" />

